docs.abstract: Minutes from the Federal Reserve’s July 27-28 meeting showed that “most” officials “judged that the standard set out in the committee’s guidance regarding asset purchases could be reached this year.”
docs.snippet: Minutes from the Federal Reserve’s July 27-28 meeting showed that “most” officials “judged that the standard set out in the committee’s guidance regarding asset purchases could be reached this year.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Federal Reserve officials are preparing to slow the central bank’s large purchases of government-backed bonds, the first step toward a more normal monetary policy setting as the economy heals from the pandemic — but when they met last month, they remained starkly divided over just when the pullback should happen.

headline.main: Fed officials saw a path to slowing bond-buying this year, but debated when to start.
headline.print_headline: Pace of Retreat On Bond Buys Divides the Fed

docs.abstract: Most of the Afghan central bank’s reserves are frozen at the Federal Reserve. And the International Monetary Fund will block more than $400 million in aid.
docs.snippet: Most of the Afghan central bank’s reserves are frozen at the Federal Reserve. And the International Monetary Fund will block more than $400 million in aid.
docs.lead_paragraph: Despite the chaotic end to its presence in Afghanistan, the United States still has control over billions of dollars belonging to the Afghan central bank, money that Washington is making sure remains out of the reach of the Taliban.

headline.main: U.S. and I.M.F. Apply a Financial Squeeze on the Taliban
headline.print_headline: U.S. Blocks Afghan Bank From Billions

docs.lead_paragraph: When the Paycheck Protection Program began last year to help small businesses that were struggling during the pandemic, the federal government was determined to get the relief money out fast — so it waived much of the vetting lenders traditionally do on business loans.

docs.abstract: Even as the Delta variant surges, it’s imperative that the finance industry get back into the office.
docs.snippet: Even as the Delta variant surges, it’s imperative that the finance industry get back into the office.
docs.lead_paragraph: For all the endless bravado and gobs of money sloshing through Wall Street, at their core, banking and trading are apprenticeship businesses. They are akin to the Florentine guilds of the Renaissance, in which the subtleties and intricacies of art and science were absorbed over many years through careful observation.

headline.main: My Years on Wall Street Showed Me Why You Can’t Make a Deal on Zoom
headline.print_headline: You Can’t Learn the Art of Closing the Deal on Zoom

docs.abstract: As Jerome H. Powell nears the end of his term as Federal Reserve chair, Ms. Yellen will have a say over whether he should stay on. Many progressive Democrats want him replaced.
docs.snippet: As Jerome H. Powell nears the end of his term as Federal Reserve chair, Ms. Yellen will have a say over whether he should stay on. Many progressive Democrats want him replaced.
docs.lead_paragraph: Janet L. Yellen has dedicated most of her professional life to the Federal Reserve. She served in its highest-ranking roles, including as president of the Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco, on its Washington-based board and as the central bank’s first female chair. When President Donald J. Trump decided to replace her in that role in 2017, she was sorely disappointed.

headline.main: Janet Yellen Gets a Chance to Shape the Fed, This Time From Outside
headline.print_headline: Yellen Has Chance to Remake Fed

byline.original: By Jeanna Smialek and Alan Rappeport

docs.abstract: The yield on the 10-year Treasury note is often a reliable indicator of how Wall Street views the prospects of economic growth — especially when other data points send confusing signals.
docs.snippet: The yield on the 10-year Treasury note is often a reliable indicator of how Wall Street views the prospects of economic growth — especially when other data points send confusing signals.
docs.lead_paragraph: There are many ways to assess the prospects for economic growth — from the performance of the stock market, to the latest unemployment data, to inflation. But when none of those send a clear signal about the state of the economy, there’s one reading that investors, traders and economists often rely on: the yield on the 10-year Treasury note.

headline.main: One Number to Gauge Where the Economy Is Headed
headline.print_headline: Falling Yields For T-Notes Signal Angst

docs.abstract: More money could help attract and retain junior bankers, but pandemic precautions could also become a differentiator in Wall Street’s war for talent.
docs.snippet: More money could help attract and retain junior bankers, but pandemic precautions could also become a differentiator in Wall Street’s war for talent.
docs.lead_paragraph: Hardly a day goes by without a big bank announcing a significant rise in starting salaries for its youngest employees. JPMorgan Chase, Citigroup, UBS and Morgan Stanley are now paying first-year bankers $100,000, while Evercore, Jefferies and Goldman Sachs will pay $110,000. In most cases, base salaries for first-year analysts were previously $85,000 to $95,000.

headline.main: Big banks are raising salaries for junior staff to counter burnout.
headline.print_headline: Banks Boost Junior Pay To Counter the Burnout

docs.abstract: Regulators want to fix the property sector’s bad habit of borrowing too much. Evergrande, with its billions of dollars in debt, may stand in the way.
docs.snippet: Regulators want to fix the property sector’s bad habit of borrowing too much. Evergrande, with its billions of dollars in debt, may stand in the way.
docs.lead_paragraph: The company owes hundreds of billions of dollars. Its creditors are circling. Its shares have taken a beating. But if anything forces a reckoning for Evergrande, a vast real estate empire in China, it might be the nervousness of ordinary home buyers like Chen Cheng.

headline.main: Evergrande Went From China’s Biggest Developer to One of Its Worst Debtors
headline.print_headline: ‘Gray Rhino’ Has Run Up A Huge Debt

byline.original: By Alexandra Stevenson and Cao Li
